"# Chapter 3 — Closures & Captured State

A closure is a function that remembers. When you build a function inside another function, the inner one can see the outer one's variables — and even after the outer function has returned, that inner function keeps those variables alive, private, and ready. It's the simplest way to give a piece of code its own memory without reaching for anything global or complicated.

This matters because so many real tasks need *state that evolves but stays contained*: a counter that increments each time you call it, a memo table that remembers expensive calculations, a little generator that hands you the next item in a sequence. Closures let you build these tools cleanly, in pure Scheme, with no side doors or magic. The outer function runs once, sets up the state, and returns an inner function that closes over it. Every time you call that returned function, it sees and can update the same captured variables. It's local, it's safe, and it composes beautifully.

In this chapter we'll build counters, toggles, accumulators, memo tables, and small stateful pipelines — each one a complete program that runs top to bottom and shows what closures unlock. By the end, you'll see how to orchestrate verbs that need to remember what they've seen, route around failure when state gets stale, and keep everything honest and restrained.

---

## A Simple Counter

The warmup: a closure that captures a single number and increments it each time you call the returned function. This is the foundational pattern — one outer function runs, one inner function remembers.

```scheme
;; A counter that increments and returns its current value each time called.
(define make-counter
  (lambda (start)
    (let ((count start))
      (lambda ()
        (set! count (+ count 1))
        count))))

(define my-counter (make-counter 0))

(list
  (my-counter)   ;; => 1
  (my-counter)   ;; => 2
  (my-counter))  ;; => 3
```

The outer `lambda` runs once, binding `count` to `start`. The inner `lambda` — the one we return — sees `count` and can mutate it with `set!`. Each call advances the state. The variable `count` is private to this closure; no other code can touch it.

---

## A Toggle

Same shape, different behavior: a closure that flips between two states. Each call returns the current state and switches to the other.

```scheme
;; A toggle that alternates between two values each time called.
(define make-toggle
  (lambda (a b)
    (let ((current a)
          (other b))
      (lambda ()
        (let ((result current))
          (set! current other)
          (set! other result)
          result)))))

(define light (make-toggle 'on 'off))

(list
  (light)   ;; => on
  (light)   ;; => off
  (light)   ;; => on
  (light))  ;; => off
```

We capture two values and swap them on each call. The closure remembers both, and the caller just sees the sequence. This is BACK in action — the simplest program that honestly toggles, no extra machinery.

---

## An Accumulator

A closure that collects values over multiple calls and returns the running total. This is the classic accumulator pattern: one function adds, another retrieves.

```scheme
;; An accumulator that sums values added to it and returns the total.
(define make-accumulator
  (lambda ()
    (let ((total 0))
      (lambda (n)
        (set! total (+ total n))
        total))))

(define acc (make-accumulator))

(list
  (acc 5)    ;; => 5
  (acc 10)   ;; => 15
  (acc -3)   ;; => 12
  (acc 0))   ;; => 12
```

Each call to `acc` adds its argument to `total` and returns the new sum. The state lives entirely inside the closure.

---

## A Stateful Filter

Now we compose: a closure that remembers which items it's already seen and filters them out of subsequent calls. This brings together captured state and list processing.

```scheme
;; A filter that remembers seen items and only passes new ones.
(define make-unique-filter
  (lambda ()
    (let ((seen '()))
      (lambda (items)
        (let loop ((remaining items)
                   (result '()))
          (if (null? remaining)
              (reverse result)
              (let ((item (car remaining)))
                (if (member item seen)
                    (loop (cdr remaining) result)
                    (begin
                      (set! seen (cons item seen))
                      (loop (cdr remaining) (cons item result)))))))))))

(define uniq (make-unique-filter))

(list
  (uniq '(a b c))       ;; => (a b c)
  (uniq '(b c d e))     ;; => (d e)
  (uniq '(a e f)))      ;; => (f)
```

The closure captures `seen`, initially empty. Each call walks the input list: if an item is already in `seen`, skip it; otherwise, add it to `seen` and pass it through. The state accumulates across calls, and each call sees the updated history.

---

## A Counter with Reset

Sometimes you need to inspect or reset the state. A closure can return multiple functions — a little dispatch table — each closing over the same variables.

```scheme
;; A counter with increment, read, and reset operations.
(define make-counter-with-reset
  (lambda (start)
    (let ((count start))
      (lambda (op)
        (cond
          ((eq? op 'inc) (begin (set! count (+ count 1)) count))
          ((eq? op 'read) count)
          ((eq? op 'reset) (begin (set! count start) count))
          (else 'unknown-op))))))

(define counter (make-counter-with-reset 0))

(list
  (counter 'inc)     ;; => 1
  (counter 'inc)     ;; => 2
  (counter 'read)    ;; => 2
  (counter 'reset)   ;; => 0
  (counter 'inc))    ;; => 1
```

One closure, three operations. The `op` argument routes to the right action, and all three see the same `count`. This is FORWARD: we're routing control flow *inside* the closure to advance the computation cleanly.

---

## A Memo Table

A closure that caches expensive calculations: if you ask for the same input twice, it returns the cached result instead of recalculating. This is the classic memoization pattern, and it's pure closure magic.

```scheme
;; A memoized square function that caches results.
(define make-memo-square
  (lambda ()
    (let ((cache '()))
      (lambda (n)
        (let ((cached (assoc n cache)))
          (if cached
              (cdr cached)
              (let ((result (* n n)))
                (set! cache (cons (cons n result) cache))
                result)))))))

(define memo-square (make-memo-square))

(list
  (memo-square 5)    ;; => 25 (calculated)
  (memo-square 7)    ;; => 49 (calculated)
  (memo-square 5)    ;; => 25 (cached)
  (memo-square 7))   ;; => 49 (cached)
```

The closure captures `cache`, an association list mapping inputs to outputs. On each call, we check `cache` with `assoc`: if the input is there, return the stored result; otherwise, compute it, store it, and return it. The cache grows over time, private to this function.

---

## A Stateful Mapper

A closure that applies a function to each item in a list, but keeps a running count of how many items it's processed across all calls.

```scheme
;; A mapper that tracks total items processed across all calls.
(define make-counting-mapper
  (lambda (f)
    (let ((total 0))
      (lambda (items)
        (let ((mapped (map f items)))
          (set! total (+ total (length items)))
          (list 'result mapped 'total total))))))

(define double-counter (make-counting-mapper (lambda (x) (* x 2))))

(list
  (double-counter '(1 2 3))      ;; => (result (2 4 6) total 3)
  (double-counter '(4 5))        ;; => (result (8 10) total 5)
  (double-counter '(6 7 8 9)))   ;; => (result (12 14 16 18) total 9)
```

The closure captures `total`, increments it by the length of each input list, and returns both the mapped result and the running total. The state persists, and each call sees the updated count.

---

## A Stateful Validator with History

A closure that validates strings against a regex-like pattern (here, just checking length), remembers which strings passed, and returns both the validation result and the history.

```scheme
;; A validator that remembers all strings that passed validation.
(define make-validating-logger
  (lambda (min-length)
    (let ((passed '()))
      (lambda (s)
        (let ((valid (>= (string-length s) min-length)))
          (if valid
              (set! passed (cons s passed))
              'ok)
          (list 'valid valid 'history (reverse passed)))))))

(define logger (make-validating-logger 3))

(list
  (logger \"hi\")       ;; => (valid #f history ())
  (logger \"hello\")    ;; => (valid #t history (\"hello\"))
  (logger \"yo\")       ;; => (valid #f history (\"hello\"))
  (logger \"world\"))   ;; => (valid #t history (\"hello\" \"world\"))
```

The closure captures `passed`, a list of all valid strings. Each call checks the length, updates `passed` if valid, and returns both the validation result and the history so far.

---

## A Rate Limiter

A closure that enforces a simple rate limit: it remembers the last time it was called (as a count, not real time for simplicity here), and rejects calls that come too soon.

```scheme
;; A rate limiter that rejects calls within N ticks of the last allowed call.
(define make-rate-limiter
  (lambda (min-gap)
    (let ((last-tick -1000))
      (lambda (current-tick)
        (if (>= (- current-tick last-tick) min-gap)
            (begin
              (set! last-tick current-tick)
              'allowed)
            'rejected)))))

(define limiter (make-rate-limiter 5))

(list
  (limiter 0)    ;; => allowed
  (limiter 2)    ;; => rejected
  (limiter 5)    ;; => allowed
  (limiter 9)    ;; => rejected
  (limiter 10))  ;; => allowed
```

The closure captures `last-tick`, initially set far in the past. Each call checks if enough ticks have passed; if so, it updates `last-tick` and allows the call. Otherwise, it rejects. This is ESCAPE in code: the closure routes the failure (rejection) cleanly and honestly.

---

## A Cycle Generator

A closure that cycles through a list of values, returning the next one on each call and wrapping back to the start after the last.

```scheme
;; A cycle generator that returns the next item in a list, wrapping around.
(define make-cycle
  (lambda (items)
    (let ((current items))
      (lambda ()
        (if (null? current)
            (set! current items)
            'ok)
        (let ((result (car current)))
          (set! current (cdr current))
          result)))))

(define colors (make-cycle '(red green blue)))

(list
  (colors)   ;; => red
  (colors)   ;; => green
  (colors)   ;; => blue
  (colors)   ;; => red
  (colors))  ;; => green
```

The closure captures `current`, a pointer into the list. Each call returns the head, advances the pointer, and resets to the full list when it reaches the end. It's an infinite generator, stateful and pure.

---

## A Stateful Fold

A closure that performs a fold (reduce) but remembers the accumulator across calls, so you can fold incrementally over multiple batches of data.

```scheme
;; A stateful fold that accumulates values across multiple calls.
(define make-stateful-fold
  (lambda (f init)
    (let ((acc init))
      (lambda (items)
        (set! acc (fold f acc items))
        acc))))

(define summer (make-stateful-fold + 0))

(list
  (summer '(1 2 3))    ;; => 6
  (summer '(4 5))      ;; => 15
  (summer '(6 7 8)))   ;; => 36
```

The closure captures `acc`, the fold's accumulator. Each call folds the input list into `acc` and updates it. The fold's state persists, and you can feed it data in chunks.

---

## A Unique ID Generator

A closure that hands out unique IDs, incrementing an internal counter each time. This is a common need when building data structures on the fly.

```scheme
;; A unique ID generator that returns incrementing integers.
(define make-id-gen
  (lambda ()
    (let ((next-id 0))
      (lambda ()
        (let ((id next-id))
          (set! next-id (+ next-id 1))
          id)))))

(define gen-id (make-id-gen))

(list
  (gen-id)   ;; => 0
  (gen-id)   ;; => 1
  (gen-id)   ;; => 2
  (gen-id))  ;; => 3
```

The closure captures `next-id`, returns it, and increments. Each call gets a fresh, unique integer. This is BACK: the absolute simplest ID generator that works.

---

## A Stateful Grouper

A closure that groups items by a key function, maintaining the groups across multiple calls. Each call adds its items to the existing groups and returns the full state.

```scheme
;; A grouper that accumulates items by key across multiple calls.
(define make-grouper
  (lambda (key-fn)
    (let ((groups '()))
      (lambda (items)
        (for-each
          (lambda (item)
            (let* ((key (key-fn item))
                   (existing (assoc key groups)))
              (if existing
                  (set-cdr! existing (cons item (cdr existing)))
                  (set! groups (cons (cons key (list item)) groups)))))
          items)
        groups))))

(define grouper (make-grouper (lambda (x) (modulo x 3))))

(list
  (grouper '(1 2 3))       ;; => ((0 3) (2 2) (1 1))
  (grouper '(4 5 6))       ;; => ((0 6 3) (2 5 2) (1 4 1))
  (grouper '(7 8)))        ;; => ((2 8 5 2) (1 7 4 1) (0 6 3))
```

The closure captures `groups`, an association list where each key maps to a list of items. Each call walks the input items, computes the key, and either appends to an existing group or creates a new one. The state grows over time, and each call sees the full accumulated groups.

---

## A Closure with Wired Verbs: Remembering Timestamps

Now we bring in the real wired surface. A closure that calls a verb (`time/unix-now`) to remember when it was last invoked, and reports how long since.

```scheme
;; A closure that remembers the last time it was called (using time/unix-now).
(define make-last-called
  (lambda ()
    (let ((last-time 'never))
      (lambda ()
        (let ((now (time/unix-now)))
          (if (eq? now 'nan)
              'time-unavailable
              (let ((result (if (eq? last-time 'never)
                                'first-call
                                (- now last-time))))
                (set! last-time now)
                result)))))))

(define tracker (make-last-called))

;; First call: returns 'first-call and remembers the timestamp.
;; Subsequent calls: return seconds elapsed since last call.
(list
  (tracker)   ;; => first-call
  (tracker)   ;; => (some small number of seconds)
  (tracker))  ;; => (some small number of seconds)
```

The closure captures `last-time`, initially `'never`. On each call, it fetches the current Unix timestamp with `time/unix-now`. If the verb fails (returns `'nan`), we escalate cleanly with `'time-unavailable`. Otherwise, if it's the first call, return `'first-call`; if not, compute and return the difference. Then update `last-time`. This is ESCAPE: we check for `'nan` and route around it.

---

## A Memo Table with Wired Verb: Hashing Strings

A closure that memoizes the SHA256 hash of strings using `system/sha256`. If you ask for the same string twice, it returns the cached hash.

```scheme
;; A memoized hash function using system/sha256.
(define make-memo-hasher
  (lambda ()
    (let ((cache '()))
      (lambda (s)
        (let ((cached (assoc s cache)))
          (if cached
              (cdr cached)
              (let ((hash (system/sha256 s)))
                (if (eq? hash 'nan)
                    'hash-failed
                    (begin
                      (set! cache (cons (cons s hash) cache))
                      hash)))))))))

(define hasher (make-memo-hasher))

(list
  (hasher \"hello\")    ;; => (hash, calculated and cached)
  (hasher \"world\")    ;; => (hash, calculated and cached)
  (hasher \"hello\"))   ;; => (hash, retrieved from cache)
```

The closure captures `cache`. On each call, we check if the string is already in the cache. If so, return the cached hash. If not, call `system/sha256`. If it fails (`'nan`), return `'hash-failed`; otherwise, cache and return the hash. This is honest verb handling: always check, always route failure cleanly.

---

## A Stateful UUID Generator with Deduplication

A closure that generates UUIDs using `system/uuid-v4` and remembers all previously generated ones to detect (impossible but theoretically possible) collisions.

```scheme
;; A UUID generator that tracks all generated UUIDs and detects collisions.
(define make-uuid-tracker
  (lambda ()
    (let ((seen '()))
      (lambda ()
        (let ((uuid (system/uuid-v4)))
          (if (eq? uuid 'nan)
              'uuid-failed
              (if (member uuid seen)
                  (list 'collision uuid)
                  (begin
                    (set! seen (cons uuid seen))
                    (list 'ok uuid 'total (length seen))))))))))

(define uuid-gen (make-uuid-tracker))

(list
  (uuid-gen)   ;; => (ok <uuid> total 1)
  (uuid-gen)   ;; => (ok <uuid> total 2)
  (uuid-gen))  ;; => (ok <uuid> total 3)
```

The closure captures `seen`, a list of all UUIDs generated so far. Each call invokes `system/uuid-v4`. If it fails, return `'uuid-failed`. If the UUID is already in `seen` (a collision), report it. Otherwise, add it to `seen` and return success with the total count. This is FORWARD: we're advancing the computation (generating, checking, recording) in one clean flow.

---

## A Stateful Web Scraper with Caching

A closure that fetches web pages using `web/fetch` and caches the results. If you request the same URL twice, it returns the cached content without re-fetching.

```scheme
;; A web fetcher with per-URL caching.
(define make-cached-fetcher
  (lambda ()
    (let ((cache '()))
      (lambda (url)
        (let ((cached (assoc url cache)))
          (if cached
              (list 'cached (cdr cached))
              (let ((result (web/fetch url)))
                (if (or (eq? result 'nan) (eq? (car result) 'escalate))
                    (list 'fetch-failed url)
                    (begin
                      (set! cache (cons (cons url result) cache))
                      (list 'fresh result))))))))))

(define fetcher (make-cached-fetcher))

;; Example: fetcher will cache results per URL.
(list
  (fetcher \"https://example.com\")   ;; => (fresh <content>)
  (fetcher \"https://example.org\")   ;; => (fresh <content>)
  (fetcher \"https://example.com\"))  ;; => (cached <content>)
```

The closure captures `cache`, an association list mapping URLs to fetch results. On each call, check the cache first. If the URL is there, return `(cached ...)`. If not, call `web/fetch`. If it fails (returns `'nan` or `(escalate ...)`), return `'fetch-failed`. Otherwise, cache the result and return `(fresh ...)`. This is ESCAPE and FORWARD together: we check for failure and route it cleanly, then advance the computation by caching.

---

## A Stateful Retry Counter

A closure that wraps a verb call and tracks how many times it's been retried. If the verb fails, it increments a retry count; if it succeeds, it resets the count.

```scheme
;; A retry tracker for a verb that might fail.
(define make-retry-tracker
  (lambda (verb-fn)
    (let ((retries 0))
      (lambda ()
        (let ((result (verb-fn)))
          (if (or (eq? result 'nan) (and (pair? result) (eq? (car result) 'escalate)))
              (begin
                (set! retries (+ retries 1))
                (list 'failed 'retries retries))
              (begin
                (set! retries 0)
                (list 'ok result))))))))

(define unstable-verb
  (let ((counter 0))
    (lambda ()
      (set! counter (+ counter 1))
      (if (< counter 3) 'nan 'success))))

(define tracker (make-retry-tracker unstable-verb))

(list
  (tracker)   ;; => (failed retries 1)
  (tracker)   ;; => (failed retries 2)
  (tracker)   ;; => (ok success)
  (tracker))  ;; => (ok success)
```

The closure captures `retries`. Each call invokes the verb. If it fails, increment `retries` and return the count. If it succeeds, reset `retries` to zero and return the result. This is ESCAPE: we track and report failure honestly without crashing.

---

## A Stateful Aggregator with System Time

A closure that aggregates numeric values and timestamps each batch using `system/timestamp`. It returns both the running total and a log of when each batch was added.

```scheme
;; An aggregator that timestamps each batch added.
(define make-timestamped-aggregator
  (lambda ()
    (let ((total 0)
          (log '()))
      (lambda (values)
        (let ((sum (fold + 0 values))
              (ts (system/timestamp)))
          (if (eq? ts 'nan)
              'timestamp-failed
              (begin
                (set! total (+ total sum))
                (set! log (cons (list 'time ts 'added sum) log))
                (list 'total total 'log (reverse log)))))))))

(define agg (make-timestamped-aggregator))

(list
  (agg '(1 2 3))     ;; => (total 6 log ((time <ts> added 6)))
  (agg '(4 5))       ;; => (total 15 log ((time <ts> added 6) (time <ts> added 9)))
  (agg '(10)))       ;; => (total 25 log (...))
```

The closure captures `total` and `log`. Each call sums the input values, fetches a timestamp, checks for `'nan`, and if successful, updates `total` and appends an entry to `log`. It returns both the running total and the full log. This is FORWARD: each call advances the state (sum, timestamp, log) in a clean pipeline.

---

## A Closure Managing Multiple Counters

A closure that maintains a named set of counters. You pass a name and an operation (`'inc` or `'read`), and it routes to the right counter or creates a new one if needed.

```scheme
;; A multi-counter manager with per-name state.
(define make-counter-manager
  (lambda ()
    (let ((counters '()))
      (lambda (name op)
        (let ((entry (assoc name counters)))
          (cond
            ((eq? op 'read)
             (if entry (cdr entry) 0))
            ((eq? op 'inc)
             (if entry
                 (begin
                   (set-cdr! entry (+ (cdr entry) 1))
                   (cdr entry))
                 (begin
                   (set! counters (cons (cons name 1) counters))
                   1)))
            (else 'unknown-op)))))))

(define mgr (make-counter-manager))

(list
  (mgr 'clicks 'inc)    ;; => 1
  (mgr 'clicks 'inc)    ;; => 2
  (mgr 'views 'inc)     ;; => 1
  (mgr 'clicks 'read)   ;; => 2
  (mgr 'views 'read))   ;; => 1
```

The closure captures `counters`, an association list mapping names to counts. Each call looks up the name. If it's a read, return the count (or 0 if not found). If it's an increment, update or create the entry. This is a dispatch table inside a closure, and it shows how one closure can manage multiple independent states.

---

## A Stateful JSON Accumulator

A closure that accumulates JSON-like association lists and merges them over multiple calls, so you can build up a complex structure incrementally.

```scheme
;; A JSON accumulator that merges alists across calls.
(define make-json-accumulator
  (lambda ()
    (let ((data '()))
      (lambda (new-alist)
        (for-each
          (lambda (pair)
            (let* ((key (car pair))
                   (val (cdr pair))
                   (existing (assoc key data)))
              (if existing
                  (set-cdr! existing val)
                  (set! data (cons pair data)))))
          new-alist)
        data))))

(define json-acc (make-json-accumulator))

(list
  (json-acc '((name . \"Alice\") (age . 30)))       ;; => ((name . \"Alice\") (age . 30))
  (json-acc '((age . 31) (city . \"NYC\")))         ;; => ((city . \"NYC\") (age . 31) (name . \"Alice\"))
  (json-acc '((name . \"Alicia\"))))                ;; => ((name . \"Alicia\") (city . \"NYC\") (age . 31))
```

The closure captures `data`, an association list. Each call walks the input alist: if a key already exists, update its value; otherwise, add the pair. This is useful for building up configuration or state from multiple sources. It's BACK: the simplest merge that works, no fancier data structure needed.

---

## A Closure Wrapping a Model Call with History

A closure that calls `model/fast` with a prompt and remembers all previous prompts and responses, so you can review the conversation history.

```scheme
;; A model caller that logs all prompts and responses.
(define make-model-logger
  (lambda ()
    (let ((history '()))
      (lambda (prompt)
        (let ((response (model/fast prompt)))
          (if (or (eq? response 'nan) (and (pair? response) (eq? (car response) 'escalate)))
              (list 'model-failed prompt)
              (begin
                (set! history (cons (list 'prompt prompt 'response response) history))
                (list 'response response 'history-length (length history)))))))))

(define model-log (make-model-logger))

(list
  (model-log \"What is 2+2?\")       ;; => (response <answer> history-length 1)
  (model-log \"What is the capital of France?\"))  ;; => (response <answer> history-length 2)
```

The closure captures `history`. Each call invokes `model/fast`. If it fails, return `'model-failed`. Otherwise, append the prompt and response to `history` and return the response plus the history length. This is FORWARD and ESCAPE: we advance the computation (call the model, log the result) and handle failure cleanly.

---

## A Stateful Filter with Verb: Unique Hashes

A closure that hashes incoming strings with `system/hash256` and filters out any string whose hash has been seen before. This combines stateful filtering with verb orchestration.

```scheme
;; A filter that passes only strings with unique hashes.
(define make-unique-hash-filter
  (lambda ()
    (let ((seen-hashes '()))
      (lambda (strings)
        (let loop ((remaining strings)
                   (result '()))
          (if (null? remaining)
              (reverse result)
              (let* ((s (car remaining))
                     (hash (system/hash256 s)))
                (if (eq? hash 'nan)
                    (loop (cdr remaining) result)  ;; Skip if hash fails
                    (if (member hash seen-hashes)
                        (loop (cdr remaining) result)  ;; Skip if hash seen
                        (begin
                          (set! seen-hashes (cons hash seen-hashes))
                          (loop (cdr remaining) (cons s result))))))))))))

(define hash-filter (make-unique-hash-filter))

(list
  (hash-filter '(\"hello\" \"world\" \"hello\"))   ;; => (\"hello\" \"world\")
  (hash-filter '(\"world\" \"foo\" \"bar\"))       ;; => (\"foo\" \"bar\")
  (hash-filter '(\"hello\" \"baz\")))            ;; => (\"baz\")
```

The closure captures `seen-hashes`. Each call walks the input strings, hashing each one. If the hash fails, skip the string (ESCAPE). If the hash has been seen, skip it. Otherwise, add the hash to `seen-hashes` and pass the string through. The state persists across calls, and the filter gets smarter over time.

---

## A Stateful Slug Generator

A closure that generates URL slugs from strings using `system/slugify` and ensures each slug is unique by appending a counter if needed.

```scheme
;; A slug generator that ensures uniqueness by appending a counter.
(define make-unique-slugger
  (lambda ()
    (let ((seen '()))
      (lambda (s)
        (let ((base-slug (system/slugify s)))
          (if (eq? base-slug 'nan)
              'slugify-failed
              (let loop ((candidate base-slug)
                         (n 1))
                (if (member candidate seen)
                    (loop (string-append base-slug \"-\" (number->string n)) (+ n 1))
                    (begin
                      (set! seen (cons candidate seen))
                      candidate)))))))))

(define slugger (make-unique-slugger))

(list
  (slugger \"Hello World\")     ;; => \"hello-world\"
  (slugger \"Hello World\")     ;; => \"hello-world-1\"
  (slugger \"Hello World!\"))   ;; => \"hello-world-2\"
```

The closure captures `seen`, a list of all generated slugs. Each call slugifies the input string with `system/slugify`. If it fails, return `'slugify-failed`. Otherwise, check if the slug is already in `seen`. If so, append `-1`, `-2`, etc., until we find a unique one. Then add it to `seen` and return it. This is FORWARD: we advance through the uniqueness check and generate a clean, collision-free slug.

