## A Closure with Multi-Verb Orchestration: Fetch, Hash, Store

A closure that orchestrates three verbs: `web/fetch` to get content, `system/sha256` to hash it, and a captured list to store the hash. It returns a log of all fetched URLs and their hashes.

```scheme
;; A fetcher that hashes each page and logs the results.
(define make-fetch-and-hash-logger
  (lambda ()
    (let ((log '()))
      (lambda (url)
        (let ((content (web/fetch url)))
          (if (or (eq? content 'nan) (and (pair? content) (eq? (car content) 'escalate)))
              (list 'fetch-failed url)
              (let ((hash (system/sha256 (if (string? content) content (car content)))))
                (if (eq? hash 'nan)
                    (list 'hash-failed url)
                    (begin
                      (set! log (cons (list 'url url 'hash hash) log))
                      (list 'ok 'hash hash 'log-length (length log)))))))))))

(define fetch-logger (make-fetch-and-hash-logger))

;; Example: fetch-logger will fetch, hash, and log each URL.
(list
  (fetch-logger \"https://example.com\")   ;; => (ok hash <hash> log-length 1)
  (fetch-logger \"https://example.org\"))  ;; => (ok hash <hash> log-length 2)
```

The closure captures `log`. Each call fetches the URL. If fetch fails, return `'fetch-failed`. Otherwise, hash the content. If hash fails, return `'hash-failed`. Otherwise, append the URL and hash to `log` and return success. This is FORWARD in a chain: fetch → hash → store, with ESCAPE at each stage to handle failure cleanly.

