## A Closure Managing a Least-Recently-Used Cache

A closure that maintains an LRU cache: it stores up to N items, and when full, evicts the least recently accessed item.

```scheme
;; A simple LRU cache with a fixed capacity.
(define make-lru-cache
  (lambda (capacity)
    (let ((cache '()))
      (lambda (key value)
        (let ((existing (assoc key cache)))
          (if existing
              (begin
                ;; Move to front
                (set! cache (cons existing (filter (lambda (p) (not (equal? (car p) key))) cache)))
                (cdr existing))
              (begin
                ;; Add new entry
                (if (>= (length cache) capacity)
                    (set! cache (reverse (cdr (reverse cache))))  ;; Drop last
                    'ok)
                (set! cache (cons (cons key value) cache))
                value)))))))

(define lru (make-lru-cache 3))

(list
  (lru 'a 1)    ;; => 1
  (lru 'b 2)    ;; => 2
  (lru 'c 3)    ;; => 3
  (lru 'd 4)    ;; => 4  (evicts 'a)
  (lru 'b 'x)   ;; => 2  (moves 'b to front)
  (lru 'e 5))   ;; => 5  (evicts 'c)
```

The closure captures `cache`, a list of key-value pairs ordered by recency (most recent first). On each call, if the key exists, move it to the front and return its value. If not, and the cache is full, drop the last entry. Then add the new entry at the front. This is a simplified LRU, but it shows how closures can manage complex eviction policies. It's BACK: the simplest LRU that demonstrates the pattern.

