## A Closure with Recursive State Updates

A closure that maintains a nested structure (e.g., a tree-like alist) and updates it recursively based on a path.

```scheme
;; A nested updater that modifies values at a path in an alist tree.
(define make-nested-updater
  (lambda ()
    (let ((data '()))
      (lambda (path value)
        (define (update-at-path d p v)
          (if (null? p)
              v
              (let* ((key (car p))
                     (rest (cdr p))
                     (existing (assoc key d)))
                (if existing
                    (cons (cons key (update-at-path (cdr existing) rest v))
                          (filter (lambda (pair) (not (equal? (car pair) key))) d))
                    (cons (cons key (update-at-path '() rest v)) d)))))
        (set! data (update-at-path data path value))
        data))))

(define updater (make-nested-updater))

(list
  (updater '(a b) 1)       ;; => ((a . ((b . 1))))
  (updater '(a c) 2)       ;; => ((a . ((c . 2) (b . 1))))
  (updater '(a b) 3))      ;; => ((a . ((b . 3) (c . 2))))
```

The closure captures `data`, a nested alist. Each call updates the value at the given path, recursively walking the structure. If a key doesn't exist, it's created. This is FORWARD: we advance the state recursively, building up the structure as needed.

