## A Stateful Rate-Limited Fetcher

A closure that wraps `web/fetch` with a rate limiter: it remembers the last fetch time (in calls, not real time for simplicity) and rejects fetches that come too soon.

```scheme
;; A rate-limited fetcher that enforces a minimum gap between fetches.
(define make-rate-limited-fetcher
  (lambda (min-gap)
    (let ((last-fetch -1000)
          (call-count 0))
      (lambda (url)
        (set! call-count (+ call-count 1))
        (if (< (- call-count last-fetch) min-gap)
            (list 'rate-limited 'retry-after (- min-gap (- call-count last-fetch)))
            (let ((result (web/fetch url)))
              (if (or (eq? result 'nan) (and (pair? result) (eq? (car result) 'escalate)))
                  (list 'fetch-failed url)
                  (begin
                    (set! last-fetch call-count)
                    (list 'ok result)))))))))

(define rl-fetch (make-rate-limited-fetcher 3))

(list
  (rl-fetch \"https://example.com\")   ;; => (ok <content>)
  (rl-fetch \"https://example.org\")   ;; => (rate-limited retry-after 2)
  (rl-fetch \"https://example.net\")   ;; => (rate-limited retry-after 1)
  (rl-fetch \"https://example.io\"))   ;; => (ok <content>)
```

The closure captures `last-fetch` and `call-count`. Each call increments `call-count`. If the gap since the last allowed fetch is too small, return `'rate-limited` with the remaining gap. Otherwise, fetch the URL, check for failure, and if successful, update `last-fetch`. This is ESCAPE and FORWARD: we route rate-limit failures cleanly and advance the computation only when allowed.

