## A Closure with Multiple Timers

A closure that maintains multiple named timers, each tracking elapsed \"ticks\" since last reset.

```scheme
;; A timer manager that tracks elapsed ticks for named timers.
(define make-timer-manager
  (lambda ()
    (let ((timers '())
          (global-tick 0))
      (lambda (name op)
        (set! global-tick (+ global-tick 1))
        (let ((entry (assoc name timers)))
          (cond
            ((eq? op 'start)
             (if entry
                 (set-cdr! entry global-tick)
                 (set! timers (cons (cons name global-tick) timers)))
             'started)
            ((eq? op 'read)
             (if entry
                 (- global-tick (cdr entry))
                 'not-started))
            (else 'unknown-op)))))))

(define timers (make-timer-manager))

(list
  (timers 'task-a 'start)   ;; => started
  (timers 'task-b 'start)   ;; => started
  (timers 'task-a 'read)    ;; => 2
  (timers 'task-b 'read)    ;; => 1
  (timers 'task-a 'read))   ;; => 4
```

The closure captures `timers` (an alist of name → start-tick) and `global-tick`. Each call increments `global-tick`. If the operation is `'start`, record the current tick for the named timer. If it's `'read`, return the elapsed ticks since the timer was started. This is BACK: the simplest multi-timer that tracks state cleanly.

