## A Closure with Cascading Defaults

A closure that manages configuration values with cascading defaults: you can set values at a \"user\" level or fall back to \"system\" defaults.

```scheme
;; A config manager with user and system levels.
(define make-config-manager
  (lambda (system-defaults)
    (let ((user-config '()))
      (lambda (key op . args)
        (cond
          ((eq? op 'get)
           (let ((user-val (assoc key user-config)))
             (if user-val
                 (cdr user-val)
                 (let ((sys-val (assoc key system-defaults)))
                   (if sys-val
                       (cdr sys-val)
                       'not-found)))))
          ((eq? op 'set)
           (let ((value (car args)))
             (let ((existing (assoc key user-config)))
               (if existing
                   (set-cdr! existing value)
                   (set! user-config (cons (cons key value) user-config))))
             value))
          (else 'unknown-op))))))

(define cfg (make-config-manager '((timeout . 30) (retries . 3))))

(list
  (cfg 'timeout 'get)      ;; => 30 (system default)
  (cfg 'timeout 'set 60)   ;; => 60
  (cfg 'timeout 'get)      ;; => 60 (user override)
  (cfg 'retries 'get))     ;; => 3 (system default)
```

The closure captures `user-config` and closes over `system-defaults`. On a `'get`, check `user-config` first; if not found, fall back to `system-defaults`. On a `'set`, update or create the user-level entry. This is FORWARD: we route through two levels of configuration cleanly.

