## A Stateful Deduplicator with Expiry

A closure that deduplicates items but expires old entries after N calls, so the deduplication window slides over time.

```scheme
;; A deduplicator with a sliding window of N calls.
(define make-sliding-dedup
  (lambda (window-size)
    (let ((seen '())
          (call-count 0))
      (lambda (items)
        (set! call-count (+ call-count 1))
        ;; Expire old entries
        (set! seen (filter (lambda (entry) (> (cdr entry) (- call-count window-size))) seen))
        ;; Deduplicate
        (let loop ((remaining items)
                   (result '()))
          (if (null? remaining)
              (reverse result)
              (let ((item (car remaining)))
                (if (assoc item seen)
                    (loop (cdr remaining) result)
                    (begin
                      (set! seen (cons (cons item call-count) seen))
                      (loop (cdr remaining) (cons item result)))))))))))

(define dedup (make-sliding-dedup 2))

(list
  (dedup '(a b c))     ;; => (a b c)
  (dedup '(b c d))     ;; => (d)
  (dedup '(a d e))     ;; => (a e)  (b and c expired)
  (dedup '(e f)))      ;; => (f)
```

The closure captures `seen` (an alist of item → call-count when seen) and `call-count`. Each call increments `call-count` and filters `seen` to remove entries older than the window. Then it deduplicates the input items as usual. This is FORWARD and BACK: we advance the state (expire, deduplicate) in a clean, restrained way.

